	abstract = {Background Use of the FAIR principles (Findable, Accessible, Interoperable and Reusable) allows the rapidly growing number of biomedical datasets to be optimally (re)used. An important aspect of the FAIR principles is metadata. The FAIR Data Point specifications and reference implementation have been designed as an example on how to publish metadata according to the FAIR principles. Various tools to create metadata have been created, but many of these have limitations, such as interfaces that are not intuitive, metadata that does not adhere to a common metadata schema, limited scalability, and inefficient collaboration. We aim to address these limitations in the FAIR Data Point Populator.
